{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180925045555|861110558","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Mia_Love","to":"Mia Love"}],"pages":{"25741095":{"pageid":25741095,"ns":0,"title":"Mia Love","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-25T14:45:50Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Mia Love\n|image        = Mia Love Congressional Photo.jpg\n|state        = [[Utah]]\n|district     = {{ushr|UT|4|4th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2015\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Jim Matheson]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = Mayor of [[Saratoga Springs, Utah|Saratoga Springs]]\n|term_start1  = January 8, 2010\n|term_end1    = January 8, 2014\n|predecessor1 = Timothy Parker\n|successor1   = Jim Miller\n|birth_name   = Ludmya Bourdeau\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1975|12|6}}\n|birth_place  = {{nowrap|[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.}}\n|death_date   = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Jason Love\n|children     = 3\n|education    = [[University of Hartford]] ([[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]])\n}}\n'''Ludmya''' \"'''Mia'''\" '''Love''' (n\u00e9e '''Bourdeau'''; December 6, 1975) is an American [[politician]] serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Utah's 4th congressional district]] since 2015. A [[Haitian Americans|Haitian American]], Love is the first black female [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] elected to [[Congress]]<ref name=\"Will\">{{cite news |url= http://www.newsmax.com/GeorgeWill/Utah-Love-Black-Caucus/2012/09/24/id/457357/ |title= Utah's Mia Love Battles Stereotypes |first= George |last= Will |date= September 24, 2012 |work= Newsmax.com |publisher= [[Newsmax Media]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141104235235/http://www.newsmax.com/GeorgeWill/Utah-Love-Black-Caucus/2012/09/24/id/457357/ |archive-date= 2014-11-04}}</ref><ref name=\"Fox 2012-08-28\">{{cite news |url= http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/08/28/republican-convention-to-feature-rising-star-mia-love/ |title= Rising GOP star Mia Love glides into the spotlight at convention |publisher= [[Fox News Channel|Fox News]] |date= August 28, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105161139/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/08/28/republican-convention-to-feature-rising-star-mia-love/ |archive-date= 2014-11-05}}</ref> and the first Haitian American elected to Congress from the state of [[Utah]].<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.cawp.rutgers.edu/press_room/news/documents/PressRelease_11-05-14-electionresults.pdf |title= 2014: Not a Landmark Year for Women, Despite Some Notable Firsts |type= Press Release |work= CAWP Election Watch |publisher= The Center for American Women and Politics, [[Eagleton Institute of Politics]], [[Rutgers University]] |date= November 21, 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141124221853/http://www.cawp.rutgers.edu/press_room/news/documents/PressRelease_11-05-14-electionresults.pdf |archive-date= 2014-11-24}}</ref>\n\nBorn to [[Haitians|Haitian]] parents in the [[New York City]] borough of [[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]], Love was elected mayor of [[Saratoga Springs, Utah]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705357231/Saratoga-Springs-swears-in-Mia-Love-Utahs-first-black-woman-mayor.html?pg=all|title= Mia Love Wins Utah Mayoral Race}}</ref> She was previously on its city council. In 2012, Love ran for [[Utah's 4th congressional district]], losing narrowly to incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] U.S. Representative [[Jim Matheson]]. She was a speaker at the [[2012 Republican National Convention]]. She was elected as a Republican to the House of Representatives on November 4, 2014, defeating Democratic opponent Doug Owens; she also defeated him again in a 2016 rematch to win her second term.<ref name=\"Will\"/><ref name=\"Fox 2012-08-28\"/> She is currently defending her seat against Salt Lake County Mayor [[Ben McAdams]] in the [[United States elections, 2018|2018 midterm elections]], in a race rated by [[RealClearPolitics]] as a toss-up as of September 2018.\n\n==Early life and education==\nLove was born Ludmya Bourdeau on December 6, 1975, in the [[New York City]] borough of [[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]], the daughter of Mary and Jean Maxine Bourdeau.<ref name=\"MJ\">{{cite news |last= Mencimer |first= Stephanie |title= GOP Rising Star Mia Love: \"Anchor Baby\"?|url= https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2012/09/republican-rising-star-mia-love-anchor-baby |newspaper= Mother Jones |date= September 24, 2012 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105161718/https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2012/09/republican-rising-star-mia-love-anchor-baby |archivedate= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> At a time of political repression, her parents emigrated together from [[Haiti]] in 1973,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2013/09/04/mia-love-asks-how-far-away-are-we-from-losing-the-american-dream |title= Mia Love Asks: 'How Far Away Are We From Losing the American Dream?' |first= Erica |last= Ritz |date =September 4, 2013 |publisher= [[TheBlaze]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105162059/http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2013/09/04/mia-love-asks-how-far-away-are-we-from-losing-the-american-dream |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> leaving their two older children behind with family.<ref name=\"Anderson 2012-09-28\">{{cite news |first= Stuart |last= Anderson |date= September 28, 2012 |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/stuartanderson/2012/09/28/mia-love-may-be-right-about-her-familys-immigration-history |title= Mia Love May Be Right About Her Family's Immigration History |journal= Forbes.com |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105162029/http://www.forbes.com/sites/stuartanderson/2012/09/28/mia-love-may-be-right-about-her-familys-immigration-history |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Stephanie |last= Mencimer |date= October 1, 2012 |title= Mia Love May Have Been Her Parents' \"Ticket to America\" After All |newspaper= Mother Jones |url= https://www.motherjones.com/mojo/2012/10/mia-love-may-be-anchor-baby-after-all |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105162038/https://www.motherjones.com/mojo/2012/10/mia-love-may-be-anchor-baby-after-all |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> Her father had been threatened by the ''[[Tonton Macoute]],'' the secret police in Haiti, and her parents traveled to the United States on a tourist visa.<ref name=\"From Broadway to Capitol Hill\">{{cite news |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141104232826/http://www.sltrib.com/55031749-90/love-mia-bourdeau-family.html |archivedate= November 4, 2014 |url= http://www.sltrib.com/55031749-90/love-mia-bourdeau-family.html |first1= Robert |last1= Gehrke |first2= Matt |last2= Canham |title= Mia Love: From Dream of Broadway to Capitol Hill |newspaper= The Salt Lake Tribune |date= October 8, 2012 |deadurl= no }}</ref> They spoke only French when they arrived. Her father became a paint-company manager and her mother worked as a nurse.<ref name=\"corner\">[http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/296682/daughter-haitian-immigrants-gop-congressional-nominee-utah-john-fund John Fund, \"Daughter of Haitian Immigrants Is GOP Congressional Nominee in Utah\"], The Corner, ''National Review'', 22 April 2012</ref>\n\nLove's birth enabled her parents to gain a U.S. residency permit (green card) under an immigration law that favored immigrants from the Western Hemisphere who had a child born in the United States; it expired in early 1976.<ref name=\"Anderson 2012-09-28\"/><ref name=\"Deseret\">{{cite news |last= Benson |first= Lee |title= About Utah: King's dream certainly thrives along the shores of Utah Lake |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/700101394/Kings-dream-certainly-thrives-along-the-shores-of-Utah-Lake.html?pg=all |newspaper= Deseret News |date= January 17, 2011 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105164658/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/700101394/Kings-dream-certainly-thrives-along-the-shores-of-Utah-Lake.html?pg=all |archivedate= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no |quote= There was an immigration law in place, however, that would grant the entire family citizenship if Jean Maxine and Mary had a baby in America. But there was a deadline. The law was set to expire on Jan. 1, 1976. On Dec. 6, 1975, with 25 days to spare, Mia was born in a Brooklyn hospital.}}</ref>  They later became naturalized citizens.<ref>{{cite news |first= Billy |last= Hesterman |url= http://www.heraldextra.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/elections/saratoga-springs-mayor-mia-love-officially-in-congressional-race/article_5792104d-fab5-5cad-9e32-5e99f2e27b0f.html |title= Saratoga Springs Mayor Mia Love Officially Enters Congressional Race |newspaper= [[Daily Herald (Utah)|Provo Daily Herald]] |date= January 6, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121105181845/http://www.heraldextra.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/elections/saratoga-springs-mayor-mia-love-officially-in-congressional-race/article_5792104d-fab5-5cad-9e32-5e99f2e27b0f.html |archive-date= 2012-11-05 |dead-url= no }}</ref>\n\nWhen Love was five, her family moved from Brooklyn to [[Norwalk, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-mia-love-20141105-story.html |newspaper= LA Times |first1= Hohn M. |last1= Glionna |first2= Matt |last2= Pearce |date= November 5, 2014 |title= GOP hopes Mia Love's win a watershed moment for the party |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141115231319/http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-mia-love-20141105-story.html |archive-date= 2014-11-15 |dead-url= no }}</ref> Love attended [[Norwalk High School (Connecticut)|Norwalk High School]].<ref name=\"From Broadway to Capitol Hill\"/> She was raised as a Roman Catholic in the faith of her parents. After the family settled in Norwalk, her parents brought her older siblings from Haiti to reunite the family.<ref name=\"Fox 2012-08-28\"/><ref>{{cite news |first= Joseph M. |last= Dougherty |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705358639/Mayor-Mia-Love-honors-Martin-Luther-King-Jr-in-speech.html |title= Mayor Mia Love honors Martin Luther King Jr. in speech |newspaper= Deseret News |date= January 15, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141104234923/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705358639/Mayor-Mia-Love-honors-Martin-Luther-King-Jr-in-speech.html |archive-date= 2014-11-04 |deadurl= no }}</ref>\n\nLove attended the [[University of Hartford Hartt School]] with a half-tuition scholarship.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.sltrib.com/1829652-155/mia-love-searching-for-stardom-a |newspaper= Salt Lake Tribune |first= Matt |last= Canham |date= November 23, 2014 |title= Mia Love: Searching for stardom; a Mormon conversion |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141124214045/http://www.sltrib.com/1829652-155/mia-love-searching-for-stardom-a |archivedate= 2014-11-24 |deadurl= no }}</ref> She graduated with a degree in musical theatre.<ref name=\"From Broadway to Capitol Hill\"/>\n\nAfter college, she worked at Sento Corporation and the Echopass Corporation.<ref name=\"Mayor Mia Love\">{{citation |url= http://www.saratogaspringscity.com/government/mayorcouncil/mlove.php |contribution= Mayor & City Council: Mayor Mia Love |title= Saratoga Springs official website (SaratogaSpringsCity.com) |publisher= City of [[Saratoga Springs, Utah]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120911160828/http://www.saratogaspringscity.com/government/mayorcouncil/mlove.php |archive-date= 2012-09-11 |deadurl= yes }}</ref> She was also a flight attendant with [[Continental Airlines]].<ref name=\"Deseret\"/><ref name=\"Haddock 2004-09-27\">{{cite news |first= Sharon |last= Haddock |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/595094224/Political-novice-lovin-it.html |title= Political Novice Lovin' it |newspaper= Deseret News |date= September 27, 2004 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105172855/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/595094224/Political-novice-lovin-it.html |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |dead-url= no }}</ref> She moved to Utah in 1998 after converting to [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] and while working for Continental. There she married Jason Love.\n\n==Early political career==\nLove began to be active in civic affairs when she served as the community spokesperson in [[Saratoga Springs, Utah]] in an effort to persuade the developer of her neighborhood to spray against flies.<ref name=\"From Broadway to Capitol Hill\"/> The city of 18,000 near [[Salt Lake City]] was established in 1997 and has had rapid growth.\n\nIn 2003 Love won a seat on the Saratoga Springs City Council. She was the first female Haitian-American elected official in [[Utah County, Utah|Utah County]]; she took office in January 2004.<ref name=\"Haddock 2004-09-27\"/> During an economic downturn, as part of the city council Love approved a transition from the agriculture tax to municipal tax. She worked with other city council members to cut expenses, reducing the city's shortfall during the economic downturn from $3.5 million to $779,000. Saratoga Springs now has the highest possible bond rating for a city of its size.<ref>{{cite news |last= Rolly |first= Paul |url= http://www.sltrib.com/52932194-82/republican-tax-love-congressional.html |title= Mia Love causing a GOP stir nationally |newspaper= The Salt Lake Tribune |date= November 19, 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141104233419/http://www.sltrib.com/52932194-82/republican-tax-love-congressional.html |archive-date= 2014-11-04 |deadurl= no }}</ref>\n\nAfter six years on the Council, Love was elected mayor,<ref name=\"Levinson 2012-01-14\">{{cite news |last= Levinson |first= Alexis |url= http://dailycaller.com/2012/01/14/aspiring-first-black-gop-congresswoman-dont-put-me-in-a-box|title=Aspiring first black GOP congresswoman: Don't put me in a box |newspaper= [[The Daily Caller]] |date= January 14, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105071330/http://dailycaller.com/2012/01/14/aspiring-first-black-gop-congresswoman-dont-put-me-in-a-box |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> winning with 861 votes to 594 for her opponent Jeff Francom.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_13741120 |first= Donald W. |last= Myers |title= Mia Love: Race not a factor for Utah's first black female mayor-elect |newspaper= The Salt Lake Tribune |date= November 9, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141104233332/http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_13741120|archive-date=2014-11-04 |deadurl= no }}</ref> She served from January 2010 to January 2014.<ref name=\"Mayor Mia Love\"/> During her term, Love led the city in dealing with natural disasters, including a wildfire, followed shortly afterward by a severe mudslide.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.heraldextra.com/news/local/north/saratoga-springs/mia-love-thankful-for-chance-to-serve-saratoga-springs/article_cf8c7b2a-a59d-5cb6-8160-f7cc83ce5d8f.html |title =Mia Love thankful for chance to serve Saratoga Springs |newspaper= Provo Daily Herald |first= Cathy |last= Allred |date= December 26, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131229000800/http://www.heraldextra.com/news/local/north/saratoga-springs/mia-love-thankful-for-chance-to-serve-saratoga-springs/article_cf8c7b2a-a59d-5cb6-8160-f7cc83ce5d8f.html |archive-date= 2013-12-29 |dead-url= no }}</ref>\n\n==Elections==\n\n===2012===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Utah, 2012#District 4}}\n[[File:Mia Love (1).jpg|thumb|left|Love in 2011]]\n\nLove ran in [[Utah's 4th congressional district]], which was created after the 2010 Census.<ref>{{cite news |last= Gehrke |first= Robert |title= Saratoga Springs Mayor Mia Love to kick off campaign |url= http://www.sltrib.com/53233798-90/love-mayor-district-congressional.html |newspaper= The Salt Lake Tribune |date= January 4, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141104233638/http://www.sltrib.com/53233798-90/love-mayor-district-congressional.html |archive-date= 2014-11-04 |deadurl= no }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Saulny |first= Susan |title= Black Mormons and the Politics of Identity |url =https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/23/us/for-black-mormons-a-political-choice-like-no-other.html |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date= May 22, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105064855/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/23/us/for-black-mormons-a-political-choice-like-no-other.html|archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> She competed for the Republican nomination against attorney Jay Cobb and State Reps. [[Stephen Sandstrom]] of [[Orem, Utah|Orem]] and [[Carl Wimmer]] of [[Herriman, Utah|Herriman]]; she won the nomination on April 21, 2012, at the 2012 Utah Republican Party Convention with over 70 percent of the vote. She faced six-term Democratic incumbent [[Jim Matheson]] in the general election, who while living in the 2nd congressional district ran in the new 4th district, losing some of his reliably Democratic constituents.\n\nNationally, Love received campaign support from [[Mitt Romney presidential campaign, 2012|2012 Republican presidential nominee]] [[Mitt Romney]] and his wife [[Ann Romney]], [[House Majority Leader]] [[Eric Cantor]], [[House Budget Committee]] Chairman and [[Paul Ryan#2012 Vice Presidential campaign|2012 Republican vice presidential nominee]] [[Paul Ryan]], and Speaker of the House [[John Boehner]].<ref>{{cite news |last= Canham |first= Matt |url= http://www.sltrib.com/53424815-90/chaffetz-love-campaign-wimmer.html |title= Chaffetz helps Love with Washington introductions, but says he won't endorse |newspaper= The Salt Lake Tribune |date= February 1, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141104233736/http://www.sltrib.com/53424815-90/chaffetz-love-campaign-wimmer.html |archive-date= 2014-11-04 |deadurl= no }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.sltrib.com/54609778-90/boehner-campaign-center-district.html |title= Love getting boost from national GOP stars |first= Robert |last= Gehrke |newspaper= [[The Salt Lake Tribune]] |date= 2012-08-01 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141104233843/http://www.sltrib.com/54609778-90/boehner-campaign-center-district.html |archive-date= 2014-11-04 |deadurl= no }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, ''[[National Journal]]'' named Love one of ten [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] to follow on [[Twitter]].<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/ten-republicans-twitter-221744599.html \"Ten Republicans to follow on Twitter,\" by Adam Mazmanian, ''National Journal'', August 27, 2012], Retrieved November 20, 2015.</ref> When speaking to the [[2012 Republican National Convention]] on August 28, 2012, she discussed lessons learned from her parents, immigrants from Haiti who fled political repression.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/765600023/Utah-congressional-candidate-gives-speech-at-RNC.html |title= 'Revive' America, Utah congressional candidate Mia Love tells RNC, draws rousing cheers |newspaper= Deseret News |agency= [[Associated Press|AP]] |date= August 28, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105180124/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/765600023/Utah-congressional-candidate-gives-speech-at-RNC.html |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> She said, \"Mr. President, I am here to tell you we are not buying what you are selling in 2012.\"<ref name=\"NatlJMiaLoveNov2014\">{{citation |url= http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2014-new-members/utah-4-mia-love-r-20141105 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20141123031221/http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2014-new-members/utah-4-mia-love-r-20141105 |dead-url= yes |archive-date= 2014-11-23 |contribution= Utah-4: Mia Love (R) |title= Almanac: 2014 New members of Congress |publisher= [[National Journal]] }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, questions arose about her parents' immigrant status. ''[[Forbes]]'' investigated a claim in an article that month in ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' that no law existed in 1976 that would have allowed Love's parents to become citizens of the United States after her birth. ''[[Forbes]]'' found that immigrants who had been residents of the Western Hemisphere could get long-term residency permits (green cards) if they had a child born in the United States. ''Mother Jones'' issued a correction.<ref name=\"MJ\"/><ref name=\"Anderson 2012-09-28\"/><ref>{{cite news |last= Gehrke |first= Robert |title =Love's story of immigrant parents called into question |url= http://www.sltrib.com/54960191-78/campaign-citizenship-family-haiti.html |newspaper= The Salt Lake Tribune |date= September 24, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141104233958/http://www.sltrib.com/54960191-78/campaign-citizenship-family-haiti.html |archive-date= 2014-11-04 |dead-url= no }}</ref> In an October 2012 interview, her father said that Mia's birth as a U.S. citizen was key to him and his wife gaining permanent legal status and ultimately citizenship.<ref name=\"From Broadway to Capitol Hill\"/>\n\nLove lost the election to [[Jim Matheson]] by 768 votes out of 245,277 votes cast,<ref>{{citation |url= http://elections.utah.gov/Media/Default/2012%20Canvass/2012%20General%20Canvass%20Report.xlsx |title= Utah Lieutenant Governor's Office, General Canvass Report, 2012 |work= elections.utah.gov |format= [[XLSX]] formatted [[spreadsheet]] }}</ref> a difference of 0.31%. She was regarded to have run a weak campaign, switching campaign managers three times, trying to \"nationalize\" the race rather than focus on local issues, and missing interviews and appointments because of rifts in her campaign staff.<ref name=tangles>{{cite news |url= http://www.sltrib.com/54522813-82/campaign-love-republican-congressional |title= Mia Love's campaign is all in tangles |newspaper= The Salt Lake Tribune |first= Paul |last= Rolly |date= July 21, 2012  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141212210722/http://www.sltrib.com/54522813-82/campaign-love-republican-congressional |archive-date= 2014-12-12 |deadurl= no }}</ref>\n\n===2014===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Utah, 2014#District 4}}\n[[File:Mia Love by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Mia Love at the 2013 CPAC in [[Washington D.C.]]]]\nIn March 2013, Love said she was seriously considering another run against Matheson.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/mar/17/gop-mayor-mia-love-thinking-about-another-run-cong |title= GOP Mayor Mia Love thinking about another run for Congress |first= Jessica |last= Chasmar |date= March 17, 2013 |newspaper= The Washington Times |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105195505/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/mar/17/gop-mayor-mia-love-thinking-about-another-run-cong |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> In May 2013 she announced she would run in 2014. {{As of|July 2013}}, Love had raised over $475,000 for her campaign.<ref>{{cite news |last= Joseph |first= Cameron |title= Mia Love raises $475K for House rematch |date= July 15, 2013 |newspaper= [[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |url= http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/311047-mia-love-raises-475k-for-house-rematch |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105200046/http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/311047-mia-love-raises-475k-for-house-rematch |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> Love was an opening speaker at the 2013 [[Western Conservative Summit]]. She spoke of the need for increased grassroots organization in the GOP, and the need to be independent from the government.<ref>{{cite news |last= Patane |first= Matthew |title= Wisconsin Gov. Scott Walker opens Western Conservative Summit |url= http://www.denverpost.com/ci_23742030/wisconsin-gov-scott-walker-opens-western-conservative-summit |newspaper= The Denver Post |date= July 27, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105200343/http://www.denverpost.com/ci_23742030/wisconsin-gov-scott-walker-opens-western-conservative-summit|archive-date=2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Love was chosen by [[Newsmax]] as an \"Up and Comer\" in their list of top \"25 Influential Women of the GOP,\" given her visible position as a young black female Republican.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Patten |first= David A. |title= 25 Influential Women of the GOP |url= http://www.newsmax.com/top25Women |newspaper= [[Newsmax (magazine)|Newsmax]] |date= August 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105200711/http://www.newsmax.com/top25Women |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> In November 2013, Love acknowledged the growing consensus that the Tea Party needed to shift away from being the \"party of no,\" disagreeing with its part in forcing a federal government shutdown over the budget.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865590533/Mia-Love-rejects-tea-party-label-disagrees-with-tactics-that-led-to-shutdown.html?pg=all |first= Lisa Riley |last= Roche |title= Mia Love says I Don't Believe in Labels |newspaper= Deseret News |date= November 13, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105201111/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865590533/Mia-Love-rejects-tea-party-label-disagrees-with-tactics-that-led-to-shutdown.html?pg=all |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> She later reiterated her support for the philosophy of the Tea Party and many of its leaders, including Utah Sen. [[Mike Lee (U.S. politician)|Mike Lee]].<ref>{{cite news |last= Hallowell |first= Billy A. |title= Conservative Star Mia Love Denies Report That She Rejects the 'Tea Party' Label \u2014 and Clarifies Her Stance |url= http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2013/11/27/conservative-star-mia-love-denies-report-that-she-rejects-the-tea-party-label-and-clarifies-her-stance |publisher= [[TheBlaze]] |date= November 27, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105100941/http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2013/11/27/conservative-star-mia-love-denies-report-that-she-rejects-the-tea-party-label-and-clarifies-her-stance |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, 2013, Matheson announced that he would not run for re-election. Love was ranked as the favored candidate due to her name recognition and characteristics of the district. In early October 2014, the ''[[National Journal]]'' listed Utah's 4th district as the number one most likely district to change hands in November.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.nationaljournal.com/hotline/latest-edition/the-hotline-s-house-race-rankings-the-30-districts-most-likely-to-change-hands-in-november-20141008 |title= The Hotline's House Race Rankings: The 30 Districts Most Likely to Change Hands in November |first= Jack |last= Fitzpatrick |date= October 8, 2014 |work= National Journal Hotline |publisher=[[National Journal]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105201933/http://www.nationaljournal.com/hotline/latest-edition/the-hotline-s-house-race-rankings-the-30-districts-most-likely-to-change-hands-in-november-20141008 |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref>\n\nIn early 2014 Love was made a member of the Republican National Committee's National Advisory Council on African-American outreach.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://flcourier.com/2014/03/06/rncs-advisory-councils-to-focus-on-minority-communities |date= March 6, 2014 |newspaper= Florida Courier |title= RNC's advisory councils to focus on minority communities |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105202243/http://flcourier.com/2014/03/06/rncs-advisory-councils-to-focus-on-minority-communities |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> On April 26, 2014 Love won the Republican nomination for the 4th congressional district at the Utah Republican Convention, with 78% of the vote at the convention.<ref name=\"NatlJMiaLoveNov2014\"/>{{Verify source|date=September 2018}}\n\nOn election night, Democratic Party nominee Doug Owens led Love until late in the evening, when she pulled ahead and ultimately won by more than 7,000 votes.<ref name=\"NatlJMiaLoveNov2014\"/><ref name=\"UtahLtGovElectRes11052014\">{{citation |title= Utah Election Results US Congressional District #4 |url= http://electionresults.utah.gov/elections/uscongress/4|work=electionresults.utah.gov |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105202824/http://electionresults.utah.gov/elections/uscongress/4 |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> Reacting to her victory, Love took a shot at the media's perceived obsession with [[identity politics]], joking to her supporters: \"Many of the naysayers out there said that Utah would never elect a black, Republican, [[Latter-day Saints|LDS]] woman to Congress. Not only did we do it, we were the first to do it.\"<ref>Bouie, Jamelle. \"[http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/mia-loves-immigrant-rhetoric Mia Love's Immigrant Rhetoric].\" ''The New Yorker''. 2014-11-29. Retrieved 2017-07-24.</ref>\n\n===2016===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Utah, 2016#District 4}}\n\nLove ran for re-election in 2016. She defeated Democrat Doug Owens in the general election with 54% of the vote, over 12 points ahead of her nearest challenger.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Canham|first1=Matt|title=Doug Owens concedes; Mia Love has 'never been more proud of this state,' which she'll serve in a 2nd term|url=http://www.sltrib.com/home/4561354-155/rep-mia-love-has-the-advantage|accessdate=11 November 2016|publisher=Salt Lake Tribune|date=November 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Meyer|first1=Theodoric|title=Utah GOP plots to save Mia Love from Drumpf backlash|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/03/donald-trump-utah-democrats-mia-love-221224|accessdate=24 May 2016|publisher=Politico|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref> [[David Scott (Georgia politician)|David Scott]], a Democratic Representative from Georgia, gave $1,000 to Love's campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/sep/1/david-scott-georgia-democrat-donated-1000-to-campa/|title=David Scott, Georgia Democrat, donated $1,000 to campaign Mia Love, Utah Republican: report|last=http://www.washingtontimes.com|first=The Washington Times|access-date=2016-09-11}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Utah, 2018#District 4}}\n\nLove is currently defending her seat against Democrat Ben McAdams. In June 2018, [[CNN]] stated that the race was considered \"consequential to both parties\" because Love has \"stood up to <nowiki>[President Donald Trump]</nowiki> on immigration\" and \"because national Democrats see McAdams as one of their best chances to gain a foothold on red turf.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/06/29/politics/mia-love-ben-mcadams-utah/index.html|title=The real race to watch in Utah this November is not Mitt Romney's -- it's Mia Love's}}</ref>\n\nAccording to political polling and reporting website [[FiveThirtyEight]], Love's votes have aligned with Trump's positions 96% of the time, as of August 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/mia-b-love/|title=Tracking Congress In The Age Of Drumpf|accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|August 2018}}, [[RealClearPolitics]] ranks the race as a \"toss up\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2018/house/ut/utah_4th_district_love_vs_mcadams-6285.html|title=Utah 4th District - Love vs. McAdams|access-date=August 23, 2018|work=RealClearPolitics}}</ref> A poll performed in June 2018 shows McAdams within 6 percentage points of Love, within the poll's margin of error.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/2018/06/27/poll-rep-mia-love-leads/|title=Rep. Mia Love leads Salt Lake County Mayor Ben McAdams by 6 percentage points \u2014 a too-close-to-call margin}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900020843/poll-love-mcadams-race-may-be-too-close-to-call.html|title=Poll: Love-McAdams race in Utah's 4th District may be too close to call}}</ref>. As of July 2017, Love's and McAdams' campaigns have approximately equal levels of cash on hand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/2018/07/13/mia-love-ben-mcadams/|title=Mia Love, Ben McAdams running neck and neck in money chase as Utah\u2019s hottest campaign gears up for stretch drive}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Mia Love by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|right|thumb|Mia Love speaking at the 2015 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in National Harbor, Maryland on February 26, 2015.]]\nWith the start of the new Congress, Love was appointed to the House Financial Services Committee.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.sltrib.com/1856877-155/ |title= Utah's Mia Love on committee overseeing banks |newspaper= The Salt Lake Tribune |date= November 21, 2014 |first= Matt |last= Canham |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150127194735/http://www.sltrib.com/1856877-155/ |archive-date= 2015-01-27 |deadurl= no }}</ref>\nLove joined the Congressional Black Caucus<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://cbc.house.gov/membership/|format=|publisher=Congressional Black Caucus|date=|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> in January 2015 after taking her seat.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://dailycaller.com/2015/01/06/republican-mia-love-joins-congressional-black-caucus-group-she-wants-to-reform/ |title= Republican Mia Love Joins Congressional Black Caucus, Group She Wants To Reform |newspaper= [[The Daily Caller]] |first= Chuck |last= Ross |date= January 6, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150127194941/http://dailycaller.com/2015/01/06/republican-mia-love-joins-congressional-black-caucus-group-she-wants-to-reform/ |archive-date= 2015-01-27 |deadurl= no }}</ref> While campaigning in 2012, Love had said that if elected, she would \"join the [[Congressional Black Caucus]] and try to take that thing apart from the inside out.\" She described the mainly Democratic Caucus as characterized by \"demagoguery. They sit there and ignite emotions and ignite [[racism]] when there isn't. They use their positions to instill fear. Hope and change is turned into fear and blame. Fear that everybody is going to lose everything and blaming Congress for everything instead of taking responsibility.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Romboy |first= Dennis |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705396842/Love-would-take-apart-Congressional-Black-Caucus-if-elected-in-Utahs-4th-District.html |title= Love would 'take apart' Congressional Black Caucus if elected in Utah's 4th District |newspaper= Deseret News |date= January 5, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105210314/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705396842/Love-would-take-apart-Congressional-Black-Caucus-if-elected-in-Utahs-4th-District.html |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |dead-url= no }}</ref> She later acknowledged the bonds created with fellow caucus members. \"As the only female Republican member of the Congressional Black Caucus, I have the opportunity every day to work across the aisle on issues that are divisive but important,\" she said. \"My faith and my belief in the humanity of every one of God's children helps me to work with my Congressional Black Caucus colleagues on important issues like criminal justice reform.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= Love |first= Mia |url= https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900014532/mia-love-recognize-that-diversity-gives-us-strength.html |title= Recognize that diversity gives us strength |newspaper= Deseret News |date= March 31, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, she was a lead sponsor along with [[Duncan D. Hunter]] of HR 2518 the Student Right to Know Before You Go Act, designed to increase the amount of information universities and colleges are required to provide prospective students.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Glum|first1=Julia|title=Mia Love's 'Student Right To Know Before You Go' Act Pushes Colleges To Provide More Data|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/mia-loves-student-right-know-you-go-act-pushes-colleges-provide-more-data-1935060|accessdate=January 2, 2018|work=International Business Times|date=March 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Love was named to serve on the [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce Select Investigative Panel on Planned Parenthood|Select Investigative Panel on Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2015/10/23/boehners-next-select-committee-focusing-on-planned-parenthood-to-be-led-by-marsha-blackburn/|title=Boehner's next select committee, focusing on Planned Parenthood, to be led by Marsha Blackburn|author=Paul Kane|date=October 23, 2015|website=Washington Post|accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Love got her first bill through the U.S. House. HR3791, which was approved in a 247\u2013171 vote, raises limits on how large community banks can grow, which Love says will make more credit available.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roche|first1=Lisa Riley|title=Rep. Mia Love gets first bill through House|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865652330/Rep-Mia-Love-gets-first-bill-through-House.html?pg=all|accessdate=29 April 2016|publisher=Deseret News|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Love introduced the Stop Taxpayers Obligations to Perpetrators of Sexual Harassment Act. Passed by the U.S. House in February 2018, the bill would prevent members of Congress from settling sexual harassment claims with taxpayer money.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Francis|first1=Simone|title=House votes to force lawmakers to pay for their own sexual harassment settlements|url=http://www.good4utah.com/news/politics/house-votes-to-force-lawmakers-to-pay-for-their-own-sexual-harassment-settlements/955325290|accessdate=4 March 2018|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Good4Utah.com|date=February 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Love became a supporter of creating federal laws against pyramid schemes.<ref>[https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900012621/mia-love-protecting-utah-direct-sellers-from-pyramid-fraud.html ''Deseret News'' op-ed by Love explaining her support of more federal regulation on direct marketing]</ref> She also supported adding multi-vitamins to the list of items that could be purchased with food stamps.<ref>[https://wholefoodsmagazine.com/news/main-news/fate-multivitamins-snap-recipients-debated-house/ article on Multivitamin issue]</ref>\n\nLove has been among those who have called on the Department of Education to not block state regulation of student loan providers.<ref>[http://utahpolicy.com/index.php/features/featured-articles/16709-rep-love-joins-bipartisan-challenge-to-ed-department-s-attempt-to-block-state-consumer-protection-laws article on Love speaking out against the Department of Education policy]</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 a defense bill included language that was co-authored by Love along with two other congresswomen that required the military to begin an investigation into the effects of military policies of doing in-depth investigations against service members who bring charges of sexual assault.<ref>[http://utahpolicy.com/index.php/features/featured-articles/16771-love-kuster-dingell-language-to-address-military-sexual-assault-passed-as-part-of-nda Utah Policy article on legislation passed with provision co-authored by Love]</ref>\n\nAlso in the spring of 2018 Love signed a discharge petition seeking to force a floor vote in the US House on a bills to change immigration legislation to do such things as grant regular status to people who came to the US without authorization when they were minors.<ref>[http://utahpolicy.com/index.php/features/today-at-utah-policy/16779-love-says-she-s-not-being-pressured-by-gop-leadership-to-back-off-push-for-immigration-vote article on Love supporting discharge petition]</ref> This time period actually saw Love advocating on several fronts in relation to immigration. She also was the co-leader with [[Pramila Jayapal]] of an effort to keep in place rules that allowed accompanying spouses of H-4 Visa holders to have work authorization while in the United States.<ref>[http://www.indiawest.com/news/global_indian/members-of-congress-led-by-rep-pramila-jayapal-urge-dhs/article_5d8a1ff4-5ae7-11e8-bbd1-7fc7af45b368.html article on pushlead by Love to keep in place broad work authorization for spouses of H-4 visa holders]</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 The Small Bank Holding Company Relief Act that Love had authored was passed into law.<ref>[http://fox13now.com/2018/05/24/rep-mia-loves-lending-bill-signed-into-law/ Fox 13 article on new law written by Love]</ref>\n\nLove is a member of the [[Congressional Western Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n[[File:Rep. Mia Love addressing the March for Life (32676930125).jpg|thumb|Love speaking at the 2017 [[March for Life]] in Washington, D.C.]] Love says she favors \"fiscal discipline, limited government, and personal responsibility.\"<ref name=\"Levinson 2012-01-14\"/> She has also said that she asks herself three questions whenever she approaches an issue: \"Is it affordable? Is it sustainable? Is it my job?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-mia-love-breaks-the-gop-mold-but-can-she-win-20120525,0,6232231,full.story|title=Mia Love breaks the GOP mold, but can she win?|last=Barabak|first=Mark Z.|date=May 29, 2012|newspaper=LA Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819094443/http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-mia-love-breaks-the-gop-mold-but-can-she-win-20120525%2C0%2C6232231%2Cfull.story|archive-date=August 19, 2012|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref>\n\n=== Abortion ===\nLove opposes abortion.<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-utah-mialove-idUSBREA4N06F20140524|title=Republican star Mia Love gets second chance to make political history|last1=Dobner|first1=Jennifer|date=May 24, 2014|accessdate=29 April 2016|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> In a speech at the 2017 [[March for Life]], she said her parents, immigrants from Haiti, considered aborting her but decided not to do so.<ref>[http://freebeacon.com/issues/mia-love-heartfelt-speech-march-for-life/ Mia Love Delivers Heartfelt Speech at March for Life]</ref>\n\nIn her 2012 congressional campaign, Love proposed deep cuts to educational spending by eliminating or reducing funding for public education, free school lunches for the poor, special education funding, college grants, and subsidized school loans. \n\n=== Environment ===\nLove has a 2% lifetime score from the [[League of Conservation Voters]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scorecard.lcv.org/moc/mia-love|title=Check out Representative Mia Love's Environmental Voting Record|work=League of Conservation Voters Scorecard|access-date=2018-01-14|language=en}}{{dead link|date=April 2018}}</ref> In 2012, Love said she would focus on opposing federal regulations, particularly those set by the [[Environmental Protection Agency]]. She supports the building of the [[Keystone XL]] pipeline. In 2014, she said she opposed the federal regulation of greenhouse gas emissions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Mia_Love.htm|title=Mia Love on the Issues|last=OnTheIssues.org|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=2018-01-14}}</ref> More recently, however, she has become a member of the [[Climate Solutions Caucus]] and has said that climate policies and economic growth are not mutually exclusive.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/opinion/4924129-155/love-we-can-find-climate-solutions|title=Love: We can find climate solutions and have a thriving economy}}</ref> Love supports Utah's effort to reclaim public land from federal agency controls.<ref name=\"reuters\" />\n\nLove's entr\u00e9e into politics occurred after she and her husband bought a house on a lake in Utah that had a growing [[midge]] population. Love says that at the urging of her neighbors, she complained to the developer of the land and prompted a regular pesticide treatment. Stephanie Mencimer of ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' wrote that \"rather than focus her political activism on cleaning up the lake, or the environment more generally, she just wanted to kill the bugs and move on.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2014/11/mia-love-congress-utah-representative-nowhere/|title=Mia Love: Representative from nowhere|work=Mother Jones|access-date=2018-01-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Economic and budget issues===\nIn her 2012 campaign, Love proposed dramatically reducing food [[entitlement]] spending like free school lunches and food assistance to pregnant mothers and the poor. She defended these proposed cuts by saying people who are poor will become dependent if they don't work for their food.<ref name=\"tangles\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=54398316&itype=cmsid|title=Mia Love's budget plan: Do her deep cuts go too far?|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|access-date=2018-01-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nLove proposed a blueprint that would cut federal spending by $750 billion, with a focus on cutting entitlements like free school lunch, special education funding, subsidized school loans, funds aimed at preventing homelessness, healthcare subsidies, Medicaid spending, and food assistance. She has said her proposed cuts are a \"nasty-tasting medicine\" needed for the country to run properly.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nLove believes that the federal government should have less power.<ref name=\"abc\">[http://abcnews.go.com/images/Politics/Love%27s%20Budget%20Proposal.pdf \"Posting on Mia Love's 2012 campaign fiscal plan\"], ABC News</ref>  Love was described as a [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] conservative in 2012.<ref name=\"tangles\" /> In a 2015 article titled \"How 'tea party' is Mia Love?\", the ''[[Washington Post]]'' wrote that \"Love's rhetoric from 2012 to 2014 changed a bit, even as her policy positions remained fairly constant\" and noted that Love had \"angered some conservatives when she questioned the tea party driven government shutdown in 2013 over Obamacare.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Henderson|first1=Nia-Malika|title=How 'tea party' is Mia Love?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/01/08/how-tea-party-is-mia-love/|accessdate=29 April 2016|publisher=Washington Post|date=January 8, 2015}}</ref> A blogger for libertarian-leaning magazine ''Reason'' described her as a \"Trojan horse [[libertarian]]\" due to her stance on homeschooling, federal control of land, and other issues.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Quinn|first1=Garrett|title=Libertarian(ish) Candidates|url=http://reason.com/archives/2012/10/22/libertarianish-candidates/1|accessdate=29 April 2016|publisher=Reason Magazine|date=November 2012}}</ref>\n\nShe also supports cutting taxes.<ref name=\"tangles\" /> She supported cuts to foreign aid and tort reform.<ref name=\"abc\" /> In 2014, Love focused more on balancing the budget, avoiding stating specific cuts needed but identifying the goal of matching spending to revenue.<ref>[http://love4utah.com/2014/06/10/six-ideas-for-tackling-the-national-debt/ \"2014 statement on spending\"], Love campaign website</ref> Love supported the March 2015 budget, which required an increase in federal employee contributions to their retirement funds.<ref>[http://www.federaltimes.com/story/government/management/budget/2015/03/26/house-budget/70480968/ House-passed budget cuts workforce, ups pension contribution], ''Federal Times'', 26 March 2015</ref> She has promoted the work of the libertarian [[Cato Institute]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe would like to cut the [[Earned income tax credit|Earned Income Tax Credit]] in half, and privatize the air traffic control system.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Same-sex marriage===\nLove opposes same-sex marriage. Following the June 26, 2013, decision by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] that overturned the [[Defense of Marriage Act]], Love stated that she was \"very disappointed,\" and that she would \"battle in support of Utah and American families.\"<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/miablove/posts/557607460947201 Facebook.com account for Rep. Mia Love], 26 June 2013 (retrieved 12 January 2018).</ref><ref>[http://i64.tinypic.com/qpq907.jpg Screen capture] of Facebook post by Rep. Mia Love on 26 June 2013 ([https://www.facebook.com/miablove/posts/557607460947201 direct URL]). Page retrieved, image captured and uploaded to archive on 12 January 2018.</ref>\n\n=== Guns ===\nFor the 2016 election season, Love received about $63,000 in donations from gun lobbyists and was endorsed by the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/interactives/2017/gun-lobbying-spending-in-america-congress/|title=The gun lobby: See how much your representative gets|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nraila.org/articles/20161012/nra-endorses-mia-love-for-us-house-in-utah-s-4th-congressional-district|title=NRA-ILA {{!}} NRA Endorses Mia Love for U.S. House in Utah's 4th Congressional District|last=NRA-ILA|work=NRA-ILA|access-date=2018-01-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]], Love said she would support raising the minimum age to purchase assault rifles such as an [[AR-15 style rifle]] to age 21.<ref>[https://www.ammoland.com/2018/02/utah-representatives-mia-love-john-curtis-proposing-gun-control/#axzz58jjC00yA Utah Representatives Mia Love and John Curtis Proposing Gun Control]</ref> She also stated that she was in favor of banning bump stocks and increasing the level of background checks needed to buy guns.<ref>[https://www.ksl.com/?nid=148&sid=46267098 Rep. Mia Love: 'Everything has to be on the table' after Florida school shooting]</ref>\n\n=== Healthcare ===\nLove favors repealing the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]], reducing federal subsidies towards healthcare, and putting caps on Medicaid spending.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Immigration ===\nLove is a co-sponsor of the Recognizing America's Children Act, which would provide a pathway for [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|DACA]] recipients to permanently remain in the country. Regarding DACA recipients she has said, \"Thousands of DACA recipients live and work in my district, contributing to their community daily. I have no interest in separating them from what is likely the only country they know\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/2017/12/05/utah-rep-mia-love-keep-dreamers-in-the-only-country-they-know/|title=Utah Rep. Mia Love: Keep Dreamers in 'the only country they know'|last1=Smart|first1=Christopher|date=5 December 2017|publisher=''The Salt Lake Tribune''|accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Love joined with Democrats in seeking to force immigration related legislation to a vote on the house floor. In June 2018 she specifically denounced the Trump administration's seperation of children from their parents when they crossed into the US under some circumstances.<ref>[https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900022010/rep-mia-love-pushing-bill-to-end-horrible-separation-of-families-at-border.html article on Love's speaking against the Trump administration policies]</ref>\n\n===Donald Trump===\nOn October 8, 2016, Love issued a statement that she would not vote for Republican candidate [[Donald Trump]] in the upcoming presidential election and urged him to withdraw from the race for the good of the party and the country.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levintova|first1=Hannah|title=Here are all the Republicans who have abandoned Trump's ship so far|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2016/10/republicans-list-trump-disavowal-groping-tape|accessdate=October 8, 2016|work=Mother Jones|date=October 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018, Love expressed opposition to President Trump's proposed tariffs on steel and aluminium.<ref>[https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900012231/utah-political-leaders-join-chorus-of-naysayers-on-trump-tariff-terms.html ''Deseret News'' on opposition to Trump's proposed tariffs]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRaised a Roman Catholic, Love joined [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] after graduating from college in 1998.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://thegrio.com/2013/12/18/mia-love-poised-to-make-a-political-comeback |title= Mia Love poised to make a political comeback |first= David A. |last= Love |date= December 18, 2013 |publisher= [[The Grio]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105171805/http://thegrio.com/2013/12/18/mia-love-poised-to-make-a-political-comeback |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> While working as a flight attendant, she moved to Utah as part of her work. She also wanted to be closer to a Mormon temple and to learn more about her faith.<ref name=\"From Broadway to Capitol Hill\"/> There she got to know Jason Love, whom she had met previously when he was an [[Missionary (LDS Church)|LDS missionary]] in [[Connecticut]].\n\nThe two were married in December 1998, four months after their first date. Love turned down an offer to appear in the Broadway show ''[[Smokey Joe's Caf\u00e9]]'' that would start two days before her marriage.<ref name=\"From Broadway to Capitol Hill\"/><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/296682/daughter-haitian-immigrants-gop-congressional-nominee-utah-john-fund |first= John |last= Fund |author-link= John Fund |title= Daughter of Haitian Immigrants is GOP Congressional Nominee in Utah |journal= National Review Online |publisher= [[National Review]] |date= April 22, 2012 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141105172202/http://www.nationalreview.com/corner/296682/daughter-haitian-immigrants-gop-congressional-nominee-utah-john-fund |archive-date= 2014-11-05 |deadurl= no }}</ref> When first married, the Loves lived in [[American Fork, Utah|American Fork]]. They have three children together.\n\nAfter her election to Congress, the Loves decided that Jason should continue his software work and maintain the couple's residence in Utah. Their three children continue to attend school in Utah and Love uses video calling and frequent return trips to Utah to remain in touch with her family.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865618904/Mr-Mia-Love-2-the-man-behind-the-congresswoman.html?pg=all |first= Doug |last= Robinson |title= Mr. (Mia) Love \u2013 The man behind the congresswoman |newspaper= Deseret News |date= January 3, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150127195335/http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865618904/Mr-Mia-Love-2-the-man-behind-the-congresswoman.html?pg=all |archive-date= 2015-01-27 |deadurl= no }}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change | title= Utah's 4th congressional district election, 2016<ref>[https://electionresults.utah.gov/elections/uscongress/4], State of Utah</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n |party   = Republican Party (United States)\n |candidate = Mia Love\n |votes   = 147,597\n |p